                <note type="article">
                    <p xml:id='OTPS54863P0'>Andrew Monroe Hardin was a businessman and public official in Mississippi during the nineteenth century.
</p>

<p xml:id='OTPS54863P1'>Born in 1819 in Kentucky, Hardin moved to Mississippi as a young man. He partnered with M. D. Haynes in a grocery and dry good store in Yazoo City in the early 1850s, and his business dealings helped him become a prominent resident in the state. Hardin was appointed the superintendent of Mississippiâ€™s state penitentiary in the late 1850s and served in that role into the early 1860s. Following the Civil War, he returned to his business and retail interests, until becoming involved in the National Grange of the Order of Patrons of Husbandry, or more often known simply as the Grange, in the early 1870s. The organization emphasized agricultural development within communities. Hardin became a state agent for the Grange and moved to St. Louis, Missouri, around 1873. He remained there for several years, operating A. M. Hardin &amp; Company, which specialized in agricultural equipment.
</p>

<p xml:id='OTPS54863P2'>Hardin moved to Tennessee in the 1880s and passed away on May 2, 1891. He was married twice, first to Martha Wilson with whom he had at least one child. He later married Frances Burrus Edmunds. Hardin is buried in Elmwood Cemetery in Memphis, Tennessee.
</p>

<p xml:id='OTPS54863P3'>(<hi rend='italic'>The Yazoo Democrat</hi>, Yazoo City, MS, January 21, 1852; <hi rend='italic'>The Weekly Mississippian</hi>, Jackson, MS, August 18, 1858, and December 11, 1861; <hi rend='italic'>The Mississippi Press</hi>, Pascagoula, MS, July 10, 1875; <hi rend='italic'>The Clarion-Ledger</hi>, Jackson, MS, November 13, 1873, and June 14, 1876; <hi rend='italic'>The Clarion</hi>, Jackson, MS, August 2, 1882; 1880 U.S. Census for District 388, Roll 734, Page 34a, St. Louis, Missouri; FindaGrave)
</p>

